# Accessibility Contract

This file defines accessibility rules for UI correctness, inclusive interaction, and semantic consistency.

It does NOT define:
- UI structure (see `ui-architecture.mdc`)
- runtime behavior (see `state-and-reactivity.mdc`)
- architecture layers (see `global-architecture.mdc`)
- styling system (see `styling-system.mdc`)

---

# 1. Core Principle

UI must be usable without assumptions about device, input method, or user capability.

Rule:
- accessibility is a default requirement, not an enhancement

## 1.1 Reduced motion (SSOT)

- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`: disable or simplify motion; no loss of functionality.
- Motion performance rules: `animations.mdc` (must comply with this section).

---

# 2. Semantic HTML First

Rules:
- prefer semantic HTML over generic elements
- avoid div/span when semantic alternatives exist
- structure content using meaningful landmarks

Rule:
- semantics > styling convenience

---

# 3. Keyboard Accessibility

Rules:
- all interactive elements must be keyboard reachable
- logical tab order must be preserved
- focus must never be trapped unintentionally
- custom components must implement keyboard behavior explicitly

Rule:
- keyboard interaction is mandatory for all actions

---

# 4. Focus Management

Rules:
- focus state must always be visible
- programmatic focus shifts must be intentional
- avoid unexpected focus jumps
- modals and dialogs must manage focus scope explicitly

Rule:
- focus flow must remain predictable

---

# 5. ARIA Usage Discipline

Rules:
- use ARIA only when semantic HTML is insufficient
- avoid redundant or incorrect ARIA attributes
- ensure ARIA roles match actual behavior
- do not use ARIA as a substitute for proper structure

Rule:
- ARIA complements semantics, it does not replace them

---

# 6. Interactive Elements

Rules:
- interactive UI must have clear affordances
- clickable elements must be identifiable as interactive
- disabled states must be clearly communicated
- loading states must not break accessibility expectations

Rule:
- interaction must be perceivable without visual assumptions

---

# 7. Color and Contrast

Rules:
- color must not be the only source of information
- contrast must be sufficient for readability
- state changes must be distinguishable beyond color alone

Rule:
- information must survive grayscale rendering

---

# 8. Text and Labels

Rules:
- all inputs must have accessible labels
- placeholders are NOT labels
- buttons must have descriptive text or accessible names
- icon-only actions must include accessible labels

Rule:
- no unlabeled interactive elements allowed

---

# 9. Dynamic Content

Rules:
- dynamic updates must not disrupt user context
- important changes must be perceivable by assistive tech
- avoid silent UI updates that change meaning

Rule:
- state changes must be announced when relevant

---

# 10. Component Responsibility

Rules:
- accessibility is the responsibility of each component
- shared components must be accessible by default
- features must not override accessibility constraints

Rule:
- accessibility is inherited, not optional

---

# 11. Anti-Patterns

Forbidden:

- div-based interactive elements without roles
- keyboard-inaccessible custom components
- missing form labels
- color-only state indication
- misuse of ARIA instead of semantic structure
- focus loss after interactions